      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "After the ferredoxin step, the electrons are transferred to NADP⁺, reducing it to NADPH, which then diffuses out of the thylakoid lumen to meet the Calvin cycle in the stroma. The light‑dependent reactions are essentially a solar‑powered “charge‑up” phase that produces ATP and NADPH, while the Calvin cycle is the “sugar‑making” phase that uses those carriers to fix carbon dioxide into glucose.\n\n---\n\n### The Calvin Cycle (Light‑Independent Reactions)\n\n**Where it happens:** In the stroma of the chloroplast.  \n**What it does:** Use ATP and NADPH to convert CO₂ into glyceraldehyde‑3‑phosphate (G3P), a sugar that can be polymerized into glucose.\n\n1. **Carbon fixation** – The enzyme RuBisCO catalyzes the attachment of CO₂ to ribulose‑1,5‑bisphosphate (RuBP).  \n2. **Reduction** – ATP and NADPH provide the energy and electrons to convert the 3‑phosphoglycerate (3‑PG) into G3P.  \n3. **Regeneration",
      "source": "target",
